<DOC><DOCNO> AP880407-0258 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-07-88 0314EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   04-07 0401</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0424</SECOND><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   G.D. Searle andamp; Co. said it will expand a programof giving heart disease drugs to the poor, a move observers sayputs the company at the helm of the pharmaceutical industry'sefforts to help the indigent.   Under a year-old pilot program, Skokie-based Searle gave $9million worth of high blood pressure medicine to 20,000 patients.The company said Wednesday it would expand its ``Patient In Need''program by making all seven of its heart medicines available.</TEXT><DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An oversupply of doctors that is widely predictedfor the turn of the century will not materialize, and there couldbe a shortage instead, two reports predict.   The reports, published in today's New England Journal ofMedicine, contradict an often-repeated prophesy that the nationwill have tens of thousands too many physicians by the year 2000and so should train fewer doctors.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter toldthe governments of Britain, France, West Germany and Spain they arerisking a trade war by their ``enormous subsidies'' to Airbuspassenger planes.   The major trade bill now before Congress would permit thecharging of extra ``countervailing'' duties on imports of theAirbus. They would be designed to compensate for the subsidies,raising the price of the foreign planes and thus improving thechances of U.S. aircraft manufacturers making sales to airlineshere.   Yeutter made his remarks Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A 32-year-old San Diego entrepreneur is wagingan unusual coast-to-coast campaign to oust the management of USSprint Communications Co., the company for which he says herecruited hundreds of thousands of residential customers.   Paul Walton brought his grass-roots movement to install himselfas US Sprint president to the nation's capital on Wednesday with aspeech to a small but curious lunchtime crowd outside the FederalCommunications Commission.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Millions of Americans have home computers, butonly about half of the adults with them actually use the machines,the Census Bureau reported.   Nearly three-quarters of children who had access to a homecomputer used it, however, the bureau said Wednesday.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The stock market soared Wednesday, as the Dow Jones industrialaverage advanced 64.16 points to close at 2,061.67.   The dollar rose against most major currencies.   Bond prices rallied in response to the stronger dollar.   Precious metals futures fell sharply.</TEXT></DOC>